  "notes": [
    "All transfer applicants must meet the University of California admissions eligibility requirements and the campus’s admission selection criteria. All requirements must be completed by the end of the spring term prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility and admission to UC Santa Cruz, visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that guarantees your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "THIS IS A SCREENING MAJOR. Screening majors require completion of specific preparatory coursework and/or a minimum GPA. For details on the specific screening requirements for this major, refer to the \" Transfer Admission Screening Policy \" below. Additional coursework listed under \"Recommended Preparation\" is not required for admission but is strongly recommended to support timely degree completion. For more information, including a list of screening majors and non-screening majors , visit the UCSC Admissions website.",
    "Some Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate Higher Level (IBH), and Advanced Level (A-level) exams satisfy UCSC course requirements. UCSC's exam credit policies may be found on the Degree Progress Unit website .",
    "Transfer Admission Screening Policy Transfer applicants must complete the articulated equivalents of the following courses, each with a grade of C (2.0) or better, no later than the end of the spring term prior to starting at UCSC in the fall: General Chemistry series See \"General Chemistry Series\" below for important information CHEM 8A – Organic Chemistry BIOL 20A – Cell and Molecular Biology BIOL 20L – Experimental Biology Laboratory BIOL 20L is not required for students who have completed BIOL 20A and BIOE 20B articulated equivalents at California Community Colleges. BIOE 20B – Development and Physiology One calculus course Refer to the \"Required Major Preparation Courses\" section below for courses approved to articulate to these requirements. It is strongly recommended that community college students complete all required General Chemistry coursework for their intended major at one institution prior to transfer to UC Santa Cruz. Strongly Recommended Major Preparation In addition to the required courses listed above, transfer students are strongly advised to complete the courses listed in the \"Recommended Preparation\" section below, especially CHEM 8B – Organic Chemistry, and CHEM 8L – Organic Chemistry Laboratory . These courses serve as prerequisites for upper-division requirements, and students who do not complete them prior to transfer may need additional quarters to finish their degree. Additional Information for Transfer Prospective transfer students should prioritize required and recommended major preparation courses, and may additionally complete courses that satisfy UC Santa Cruz general education requirements as time allows. For information on incorporating general education requirements into your pre-transfer academic plan, consult with your community college counselor. Please visit the Global and Community Health website to learn more about this major. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Global and Community Health B.S. Program Statement"
  ]
